eation of what Glissant calls a "new category of literature," and in turn to the attainment of his utopian political vision. Thinking through such paradoxes, Wiedorn demonstrates, can offer new perspectives on the old questions of totality, alterity, teleology, and the potential of philosophy itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aContradiction in literature. 0aParadox in literature. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846704740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438467047423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438467047/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles